              "blockId": "s1-cb-why",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "WHY THIS MATTERS: You've probably played TimeGuesser dozens of times and absorbed a rough idea \u2014 closer guess, better score \u2014 and left it at that. That's enough to enjoy the game. It's not enough to improve at it. This section fixes that gap. By the end, you'll have a precise mental model of the engine running beneath the interface \u2014 the same way a chess player learns piece values not because chess is about arithmetic, but because knowing values enables better trade-off decisions in the heat of play."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-objectives",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "SECTION LEARNING OBJECTIVES: After completing this section you will be able to: (1) explain how TimeGuesser generates rounds and calculates per-round scores; (2) describe the non-linear banded scoring curve and what it means for effort allocation; (3) identify session-level variables \u2014 round count, streak rules, time budget \u2014 that shape cumulative score strategy; (4) distinguish productive game behaviours from common scoring misconceptions."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-round-structure",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "HOW A ROUND WORKS: A round in TimeGuesser is a single image-to-guess cycle. The game presents you with a photograph, illustration, or other visual artifact, and your job is to submit a year as your answer. A standard session consists of 5 rounds, after which your cumulative score is displayed. Each round has three phases: (1) Presentation \u2014 the image appears and a timer begins; (2) Input \u2014 you submit your year guess; (3) Scoring \u2014 the game reveals the correct year and awards a proximity score based on the distance between your guess and the answer. Your session score is the sum of all five round scores."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-scoring-curve",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE BANDED SCORING CURVE: The most important thing to understand \u2014 and the thing most players get wrong \u2014 is that the score is not a smooth, linear reward for being close. TimeGuesser uses a banded scoring system: the score curve drops steeply at first and then flattens. This creates meaningful score thresholds where the point award changes slope. In a linear system, every year closer to the answer would earn you the same additional points. In TimeGuesser's banded system, the marginal return on precision is highest when you are already close, and lowest when you are far from the answer."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-analogy",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "ANALOGY \u2014 The Parking Space: Imagine parallel parking a car. The effort to go from 'three car lengths away' to 'one car length away' is modest and gains you a lot (you can now actually park there). But the effort to go from 'six inches away from the curb' to 'three inches' is enormous for very little practical gain. TimeGuesser's scoring curve works the same way: the closer you already are, the harder you have to work for each additional point \u2014 and the fewer points that work returns."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-time-budget",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "TIME AS A SESSION RESOURCE: Every second you spend on one round is a second you cannot spend on another. Most players mentally reset their time budget at the start of each round. Expert players do not. They carry a running sense of whether they are ahead or behind on time, and they adjust accordingly. The cost of over-analysing a round is not just the time lost \u2014 it's also the cognitive fatigue that carries into the next round."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-streak",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "STREAKS AND SESSION BONUSES: Many TimeGuesser variants include a streak mechanic \u2014 a counter tracking how many consecutive rounds you have scored above a certain threshold (typically around 800). Streak bonuses reward consistency, not just peak performance. The key strategic insight: a player who scores 900 on all five rounds often outscores a player who hits 1000 twice but drops to 200 once, because a single below-threshold round eliminates all subsequent bonus eligibility."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-keyterms",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "KEY TERMS: Round \u2014 a single image-and-guess cycle within a TimeGuesser session. Session \u2014 a complete sequence of rounds (typically 5) producing one cumulative score. Session Score \u2014 the sum of all individual round scores plus any streak bonuses. Proximity Score \u2014 points awarded for a single round based on year distance between guess and answer. Banded Scoring \u2014 a system where the penalty per year of error varies: steeper near zero error, flatter at high error distances. Score Threshold \u2014 a specific error distance where the scoring curve changes slope. Time Budget \u2014 total session time treated as a shared resource across all rounds. Streak \u2014 a counter tracking consecutive above-threshold round scores. Streak Bonus \u2014 additional points awarded for maintaining a streak."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-errors",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "COMMON ERRORS: MISTAKE 1 \u2014 THE LINEAR FALLACY: Assuming every year closer to the answer earns the same points. It does not. The marginal return on precision is much higher near zero error. MISTAKE 2 \u2014 THE INDEPENDENCE ILLUSION: Treating each round as a fresh start with no connection to others. Streaks and cognitive fatigue connect rounds. Play the session, not just the round. MISTAKE 3 \u2014 THE EFFORT EQUATION: Believing more effort per round always equals better session scores. Beyond a certain point, extra effort on a hard round costs more in time and energy than it returns in points."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-misconception-01",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "MISCONCEPTION SPOTLIGHT \u2014 The Linear Fallacy: Many intermediate players believe that every year they improve their guess by earns the same number of points. This leads them to keep refining a guess long after the marginal return has dropped sharply. The correct model: extra analysis time is most valuable when your estimate is already good (within 5\u201310 years). When you are already far off (20+ years), extra time is better spent arriving fresh at the next round. [Linked: misc-01-linear-fallacy]"
            },
            {
              "blockId": "s1-cb-summary",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "SECTION SUMMARY: A TimeGuesser session is a resource allocation problem with five sub-problems (rounds). To maximise your session score: (1) understand the banded scoring curve \u2014 precision near the correct year is worth more per year than precision far from it; (2) budget your time and energy \u2014 each round draws from the same cognitive tank; (3) protect your streak \u2014 consistent above-threshold performance often beats high-variance play. These three principles are the foundation for everything in Sections 2 and 3."
            }
